Questions & Data
What is the general make up of the S&P 100? (Data Source: Alphavantage API)
How do acquisitions affect the stock price of companies directly before or after the event? (Data Source: AlphaVantage API and acquisition table)
How often do S&P 100 companies tweet, what types of tweets, who tweets the most and how they interact (if at all) with others on the platform? (Data Source: Twitter via Tweepy API)

Is there any correlation between how profitable a stock is and how long it takes to realize the maximum return?  Were there generally better or worse times to buy or sell S&P 100 stocks? (Data Source: Kaggle historical S&P 500 data set)
Data Cleanup & Exploration
Gathering overall S&P 100 data was done by taking advantage of the IEX Trading API
Utilizing df.groupby(pd.Grouper(key='date'))"  allowed us to specifically navigate the immense amount of data by date rather than the same date for each individual company.
For twitter analysis we used the Tweepy api with a user_timeline search.
Looped through each twitter handle grabbing 200 tweets at a time, 11 times for a max of 2200 tweets.  Used the max_id parameter to grab only unique tweets.
Gathered approximately 187,000 tweets
Used Regular Expression library to find the patterns for a retweet, URL,@ mention, hashtag

For the acquisition data, started with our S&P 100 list and performed a search of recent (last 2 years) of acquisitions using data collected by PitchBook.com finding out of the initial 100, 48 public companies had a recent acquisition
From the list of 48 companies, stock data was pulled using IEX Trading’s API. Most companies had a +5/-5 percent change in stock prices 5 days before an acquisition to 5 days after
A few companies had acquisitions older than 2 years which was outside the scope of the stock data, required use of .dropna to eliminate any companies without deal dates
Also used a try except statement to continue the loop if a missing deal date caused an error while converting it to a datetime object

For the historical S&P data, it was required to parse the entire S&P 500 down to just the S&P 100 using a lookup table.  Once parsed, an algorithm was developed to determine when a single stock had it minimum and maximum between consecutive days
Had to drop some stocks due to the data not being available and create multiple sub-dataframes to graph
